text: RT @NinaTotenberg: At #SCOTUS Monday, #Trump Adm. SG admitted that Census Bureau experts “still don’t know even roughly how many illegal aliens it’ll be able to identify.” A tough concession given that no census has ever excluded such immigrants before. https://t.co/dAF3GtshaE

name: NPR
text:
NEW: Dr. Scott Atlas, the controversial coronavirus adviser to the president, has resigned, a White House official tells NPR. 

Atlas is not an infectious disease expert — and his short stint was marred by political blunders.
https://t.co/7WoadjWrtm

text:
Experts suggest being extra-careful over the next week or two if you gathered with others outside your pod. That means masks, getting tested — and assuming you might be infected.

text:
The Navy will decommission the USS Bonhomme Richard after sustaining extensive damage from a July fire. Restoring the ship would have proven too costly, at $3 billion or more.

text:
"I think the message I'd like them to hear is the shortness of the vaccine development process, it's not the safety that has been compromised," says an anthropologist who has spent years studying vaccine misinformation.

name: NPR
text:
One economist estimates about 10 million Americans owe back rent. Without another robust relief bill from Congress, he expects to see "mass eviction" starting early next year.

"It's absolutely critical that lawmakers step up."
https://t.co/9xmXX4Sq23

name: NPR
text:
Dr. Deborah Birx, the White House's coronavirus task force coordinator, has this advice for Thanksgiving travelers: Assume you picked up the virus. Get tested, avoid anyone over 65 and mask up, she says.
https://t.co/8VQB53PSyY

name: NPR
text: California's unusual way of distributing unemployment benefits -- old-style Bank of America debit cards without chips -- has led to a huge backlog of fraud claims. That's also cut off perhaps thousands of people with legitimate claims. @KPBSNews https://t.co/FJ3kwuFAEj
